<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What's a good response rate on dating apps?", answer: "Average response rates on dating apps vary by gender and platform: women typically get 30–50% response rates on Tinder, Hinge, and Bumble, while men typically get 5–15%. Better-than-average profiles can hit 20% for men and 60% for women. The best single move for raising response rates is improving your photos — research from Photofeeler and OkCupid consistently shows photo quality is the biggest single variable in match and response rates." },
  { question: "How many messages does it take to get a date?", answer: "On average, 8–15 messages exchanged before someone agrees to meet in person. Successful messagers tend to suggest meeting in 5–10 messages, before the conversation gets stale. Waiting too long to ask out kills momentum — most matches that don't lead to a date stall out around message 20–30. Successful daters treat the app conversation as a means to an end (a date), not a substitute for a date." },
  { question: "How many dates before a relationship?", answer: "Surveys from Match.com and Hinge suggest that the average modern couple goes on 5–10 dates before becoming exclusive. Some couples make it official after 2–3 dates; some take 15+. There's no right number — what matters is that both people are explicitly aligned on whether they're seeing other people. The 'define the relationship' (DTR) conversation is often the moment when dating becomes a relationship, regardless of date count." },
  { question: "Is online dating worth the time investment?", answer: "For most people, yes — but it requires effort. The Pew Research Center's 2023 survey found that 30% of US adults have used a dating site or app, and about 12% of them met a serious partner this way. Compared to offline dating, online has higher volume but lower conversion per encounter. The total time investment from first message to a relationship averages 30–80 hours of active app use over 3–9 months for most successful users." },
  { question: "Why is my online dating ROI so low?", answer: "Three common reasons. First, low response rate — usually a profile or photo problem, fixable by getting feedback or hiring a profile reviewer. Second, low date conversion — usually because conversations stall too long, fixable by suggesting dates within 5–10 messages. Third, low relationship rate — usually a 'looking for the wrong fit' problem, fixable by getting clearer about what you actually want and screening for it earlier in conversations." }
]) %>

